    "caption": "Big hops, strong tail, and the world's smallest newborn for its parent's size.",
    "shortDescription": "A kangaroo's hop is actually more efficient at high speed than walking — the faster it goes, the less energy it uses, because the tendons in its legs work like springs, storing and releasing energy with each bound. A newborn joey is the size of a jellybean and crawls into the pouch by itself, moments after birth, with no help. Fun fact: Kangaroos cannot hop backward — they can only move forward, which is part of why the kangaroo appears on the Australian coat of arms."
